  "prompt": "How? Ant walks from corner A (bottom left) of front wall to the other corner C (bottom right) of rear wall of a 3 meter cubical room. Shortest route?",
  "response": "Here's how to solve this classic shortest path problem:\n\n**Understanding the Problem**\n\nThe ant can't walk through the cube. It must travel along the surfaces. The shortest path involves unfolding the cube to create a flat surface.\n\n**The Solution**\n\n1.  **Unfold the Cube:** Imagine unfolding the front wall and the bottom wall of the cube so they lie flat next to each other, forming a rectangle.\n\n2.  **Visualize the Path:** Point A will be on the lower left corner of this rectangle, and point C will be on the upper right corner. The ant's shortest path is a straight line across this rectangle.\n\n3.  **Calculate the Dimensions:** The rectangle has dimensions of 3 meters (side length of the cube) by 6 meters (two sides of the cube added together).\n\n4.  **Use the Pythagorean Theorem:** The straight line path is the hypotenuse of a right triangle with sides of 3 meters and 6 meters.\n    *   a^2 + b^2 = c^2\n    *   3^2 + 6^2 = c^2\n    *   9 + 36 = c^2\n    *   45 = c^2\n    *   c = \u221a45 = 3\u221a5 meters\n\n**Answer:** The shortest route the ant can take is 3\u221a5 meters, which is approximately 6.71 meters.\n",
